WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.460
Good day , I'm Norman Wildberger. Today, I&nbsp;
want to have a look at how the series so far&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.460 --> 00:00:17.550
on the foundations of mathematics impacts on&nbsp;
mathematics education, especially in primary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:17.550 --> 00:00:25.470
school. I thought it would be useful to&nbsp;
outline the area roughly, what the main&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:25.470 --> 00:00:32.790
subjects in mathematics are for K-12 education,&nbsp;
which is primary and high school education. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:32.790 --> 00:00:41.490
roughly, there are four main topics: arithmetic,&nbsp;
geometry, algebra, and analysis, and these roughly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.490 --> 00:00:48.900
are in order both of importance and in order&nbsp;
of historical development. Basic arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:53.640
has been around for much longer than any of the&nbsp;
other subjects, and it's also the most important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.640 --> 00:01:01.410
subject practically. Geometry has been around for&nbsp;
five to ten thousand years. It's historically also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.410 --> 00:01:09.630
very important and lays the foundation for much&nbsp;
of modern technology. Algebra is around about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:09.630 --> 00:01:17.400
a thousand years old and, of course, it links&nbsp;
closely with geometry and arithmetic. Analysis is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:24.360
more modern, starting three or four hundred years&nbsp;
ago, and it also has many important applications.

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:30.930
Okay, so within arithmetic we have topics: natural&nbsp;
numbers, integers, fractions, and decimals. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.930 --> 00:01:36.420
can expect to cover those topics within the&nbsp;
high school curriculum and underline them in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:36.420 --> 00:01:44.760
primary school. Geometry is a bigger subject in&nbsp;
arithmetic, and Euclidean geometry is included:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:44.760 --> 00:01:53.160
trigonometry, transformations, and 3D geometry.&nbsp;
I think that trigonometry is actually a primary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:53.160 --> 00:01:58.260
school subject, not the classical trigonometry&nbsp;
that you usually learn but rational trigonometry,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:58.260 --> 00:02:05.850
which you can hear about in my other series. I'll&nbsp;
talk about that more when Euclidean geometry and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.850 --> 00:02:10.980
trigonometry are really subjects that ought&nbsp;
to be developed in primary school. In algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.980 --> 00:02:16.670
we have polynomials and solving equations, which&nbsp;
are primary school topics. We have some elementary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:16.670 --> 00:02:21.290
combinatorics and basic number theory, which&nbsp;
perhaps are more at the high school level. In&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:21.290 --> 00:02:26.780
analysis, we have graphs of functions, which is&nbsp;
definitely a primary school subject, exponential&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:26.780 --> 00:02:32.210
and logarithmic functions, circular functions,&nbsp;
and integrals and derivatives, which are more high&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.210 --> 00:02:40.490
school and more advanced topics. So this is a very&nbsp;
rough outline of basic mathematics that school&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.490 --> 00:02:46.370
leavers should know. There are some minor topics&nbsp;
that I haven't included like statistics, but they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.370 --> 00:02:56.210
can be fitted in in various places. So this is a&nbsp;
basis for curriculum for primary and high school.

00:02:56.210 --> 00:03:03.110
Now let's think about some basic principles that&nbsp;
can guide us in setting up mathematics education&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:03.110 --> 00:03:08.990
at the primary and high school levels. I think the&nbsp;
first and most important point is that the content&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.990 --> 00:03:17.330
is king. What you teach is more important than how&nbsp;
you teach it. Put it another way: if a principal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.330 --> 00:03:23.510
has a choice between hiring one teacher who is&nbsp;
very strong mathematically but whose communication&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:23.510 --> 00:03:28.610
skills are lacking and another teacher whose&nbsp;
mathematical knowledge is weak but whose&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.610 --> 00:03:34.580
communication skills are very good, my advice&nbsp;
is to go for the former. Go for the mathematics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:34.580 --> 00:03:42.560
knowledge at the expense of communication&nbsp;
skills. Also, this is where the role of pure&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:51.260
mathematicians comes in. Pure mathematicians have&nbsp;
to step up to the plate and explain to educators&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:57.170
what it is that they should be teaching. You&nbsp;
can't expect educators to have a good enough&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:57.170 --> 00:04:01.340
understanding of the whole of mathematics to&nbsp;
be able to say what is important and what is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:01.340 --> 00:04:06.620
not and what should come where. That's the job&nbsp;
of pure mathematicians, and I think we overall,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.620 --> 00:04:12.680
with some exceptions, have been a little bit&nbsp;
lacking in that, and we need to improve our game.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:12.680 --> 00:04:20.270
The logical structure should always be visible.&nbsp;
Mathematics is a logical subject. It makes sense,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.270 --> 00:04:26.060
and students like it when they can see that it&nbsp;
makes sense. So the logical structure should&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.060 --> 00:04:32.090
always be there. Everything should be explained;&nbsp;
there should be reasons for all major results.

00:04:32.090 --> 00:04:39.800
In terms of the format of the classroom, I&nbsp;
think the traditional thing is best where&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.800 --> 00:04:46.130
the teacher teaches and the students listen&nbsp;
and solve problems. I think self-discovery,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:46.130 --> 00:04:51.350
even if it's guided, can easily end&nbsp;
up being a waste of time. It's hard to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.350 --> 00:04:56.240
discover mathematics. It's hard to discover the&nbsp;
right way of thinking about mathematics. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.240 --> 00:05:00.800
it's much easier if someone tells you what the&nbsp;
right way to think is, and you concentrate your&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.800 --> 00:05:07.370
efforts on understanding that explanation and then&nbsp;
working out problems. That's where the creativity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:07.370 --> 00:05:12.830
that's where the originality of students should&nbsp;
manifest itself: at the level of solving problems.

00:05:12.830 --> 00:05:20.900
Calculators and computers are unnecessary&nbsp;
for mathematics education. In some cases,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:20.900 --> 00:05:27.140
they are even detrimental. Certainly in primary&nbsp;
school, they play or ought to play no role&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:27.140 --> 00:05:36.530
whatsoever. Their use is just as a crutch to&nbsp;
replace proper understanding of arithmetic.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:36.530 --> 00:05:45.440
Get rid of the calculators. Get your students to&nbsp;
practice arithmetic with pen and paper. That's all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.440 --> 00:05:53.510
that's required. Elaborate real-life scenarios&nbsp;
are also a waste of time. Although it's nice&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:53.510 --> 00:05:59.870
to connect with reality, doing so in an elaborate&nbsp;
fashion with long-winded stories that really don't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:59.870 --> 00:06:06.590
have a lot of mathematical content is cheating the&nbsp;
students. It's making it look like mathematics is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:06.590 --> 00:06:11.510
a nice fuzzy warm subject, but really you're&nbsp;
just not giving them enough mathematics. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.510 --> 00:06:18.740
I would avoid that. Often instead, you can get a&nbsp;
lot of mathematical examples within mathematics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.740 --> 00:06:24.500
itself. That's usually the best place to look&nbsp;
for examples. And finally, I think it's good for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:24.500 --> 00:06:29.810
students to maintain contact with the historical&nbsp;
development of mathematics. There's a lot of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:29.810 --> 00:06:34.070
interesting history in mathematics, and it's&nbsp;
fascinating for students if it's presented well.

00:06:34.070 --> 00:06:40.320
Those are just some opinions that I have that&nbsp;
might guide you a little bit in terms of how to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:45.750
set up mathematics curriculum. Now, let's have a&nbsp;
look at how arithmetic, as we've developed it so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.750 --> 00:06:51.870
far, affects primary school education. First&nbsp;
of all, you'll know by now that I think that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:51.870 --> 00:06:57.390
numbers should be introduced as one stroke&nbsp;
and strings of ones. This is the natural and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:57.390 --> 00:07:03.630
historical way of thinking about numbers. Then&nbsp;
after that, one should go to the Roman numeral&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:10.920
way of thinking about numbers, not for very long&nbsp;
but just to introduce it. And then after that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:10.920 --> 00:07:17.070
the Hindu-Arabic notational system, which we&nbsp;
all use. But there should be this progression&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.070 --> 00:07:23.370
in complexity, and students should really realize&nbsp;
that it's really this number as a string of ones&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.370 --> 00:07:28.980
which is the fundamental concept. The Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;
notation just gives us names for those numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:28.980 --> 00:07:37.080
The laws of arithmetic should be explained and&nbsp;
then practiced. It is very, very important that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:37.080 --> 00:07:44.040
all students get a lot of practice with the laws&nbsp;
of arithmetic. Most weaknesses in mathematics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:49.590
even at the university level, have their roots&nbsp;
in not enough training in basic arithmetic.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:49.590 --> 00:07:58.500
Subtraction and division should be introduced&nbsp;
via natural numbers. One should not introduce the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:58.500 --> 00:08:06.060
integers or the fractions first. The natural place&nbsp;
to introduce those operations is at the level of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:06.060 --> 00:08:15.420
natural numbers. Basic number theory provides us&nbsp;
with a lot of nice examples for things to count:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:15.420 --> 00:08:22.260
primes, squares, triangular numbers, and many&nbsp;
other things that we'll talk about. They are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:22.260 --> 00:08:30.870
a good source of examples for arithmetic. And&nbsp;
finally, the most important subject in primary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:30.870 --> 00:08:35.880
school education in mathematics is fractions.&nbsp;
Okay, we haven't gotten to fractions yet,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:35.880 --> 00:08:41.070
but one should keep that in mind as the&nbsp;
main goal. If students can get out of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:41.070 --> 00:08:46.560
primary school with a good understanding of&nbsp;
fractions, then the program has been a success.

00:08:49.310 --> 00:08:56.180
Next time, we're going to talk about the&nbsp;
single most important development in all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.180 --> 00:09:03.500
of mathematical and even scientific history.&nbsp;
It's influenced dramatically our civilization,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.500 --> 00:09:09.500
all aspects of our civilization. It's&nbsp;
the Hindu-Arabic number system. I hope&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:09.500 --> 00:09:13.094
you'll join me for that. I'm Norman&nbsp;
Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:09:13.094 --> 00:09:13.400
Let me know if you need any further assistance!

